          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build and cook",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the {{beef-chuck}}, {{onion}}, {{garlic}}, {{mushrooms-chestnut}}, {{dijon-mustard}}, {{worcestershire-sauce}}, {{smoked-paprika}}, {{tomato-puree}}, {{sea-salt-fine}}, and {{black-pepper}} to the slow cooker. Pour in the {{stock-beef}} and stir everything to combine. Cook on low for 6 to 8 hours, until the beef is completely tender and pulling apart. Switch the slow cooker off. Wait 5 minutes for the liquid to stop simmering, then stir in the {{soured-cream}} until smooth. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve immediately over rice or egg noodles.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Switch the slow cooker off and wait 5 minutes before stirring in the soured cream. The residual heat is enough to warm it through without causing it to split",
              "cause": "Added while the pot was still bubbling",
              "symptom": "Soured cream has split into grainy bits"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Fry the mushrooms in butter over high heat until browned before adding them to the slow cooker. Raw mushrooms in a slow cooker release a lot of liquid",
              "cause": "Mushrooms released too much water",
              "symptom": "Sauce very watery"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add another hour on low or switch to high for the final hour. Chuck will only get more tender with time",
              "cause": "Chuck is thick and needs longer at low temperature",
              "symptom": "Beef still chewy after 6 hours"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Stroganoff was a 1970s dinner party dish that faded from fashion and came back as a weeknight option. The slow cooker version is simpler than the original, no timing required, no risk of overcooking. The beef chuck is cheaper and more forgiving than fillet or rump. Serve over rice with a green salad alongside.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
